Topic: Arrays & Hashing I
Difficulty level: 4/10

At first glance this problem might seem like a casual 2-3/10 difficulty. Some of you might've written the following answer:
int count = 0;
for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
    for (int j = i + 1; j < n; j++) { // j starts at i + 1 to prevent doubles --(1,2) and (2,1) for example,-- and the first weight being packaged with itself
        if ((weights[i] + weights[j]) % k == 0) {
            count++;
        }
    }
}
return count;

While this code will compile correctly, there is a problem. The big-O of this solution is n^2 which lands us at 10^10 operations as n can be anywhere up to 10^5. 

Pro Tip: Your solutions can run for 1-2 seconds which is generally 10^8 operations.

Let's take a look at the optimal solution now.


long long countPairs(vector<int>& weights, int k) {
    
    vector<long long> remainder_counts(k, 0);// Track how many times each remainder
    long long count = 0;
    
    for (int weight : weights) {
        int rem = weight % k;
  
        int complement = (k - rem) % k; // what remainder does it need to complete itself to k. In the case k=3 an example could be 4=>rem=1=>complement=2
        
        // If we've seen the complement before, add its frequency to our count
        count += remainder_counts[complement]; // using the same example (see line 30) if we have seen 3 numbers with the remainder 2, than 4 is going to have 3 numbers that can match with it so far that'll have the sum that has 3 as a divisor

        remainder_counts[rem]++;//for the next numbers remember that we have seen another number with this remainder
    }
    
    return count;
}


